<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-08-22T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-08-22T17:00:00-05:00" n="684" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d684">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">882.6351 U.S. Steel Corporation/20:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Minister in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Walton</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-08-22T18:00:00-04:00">August 22, 1938—6
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>35. Your 55, July 26, noon.</p>
                            <list>
                                <label>1.</label>
                                <item>Please keep the Department closely informed by telegraph of
                                    any developments that may follow the Liberian Government’s
                                    discontinuance of negotiations with Neep, particularly should
                                    any conflict arise which might affect adversely the proposed
                                    operations of the United States Steel Corporation.</item>
                                <label>2.</label>
                                <item>For your confidential information, the Steel Corporation has
                                    been requested by the Amsterdamsche Bank to receive a delegation
                                    which Neep proposes to send to the United States with a view to
                                    inviting American participation in its “initialed” iron ore
                                    concession in Liberia. The Department understands that this
                                    proposal is not meeting with a favorable reception by the
                                    Corporation.</item>
                            </list>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>